Josh Sweat stayed hot in Week 5, tallying three solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Sweat is up to five sacks on the season and has gotten to the quarterback in four straight. Sweat is a virtual must start as a borderline DL1 option for as long as he is cooking. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Armstrong was at it again in Week 5, tallying two solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Dorance is up to five sacks on the season and has recorded a sack in four of his five contests. He has been producing well enough to be counted as part of the DL1 conversation while he is hot, and should be treated as such for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against the Chicago Bears. Treat Dorance as a must-start for the tasty matchup. Add Dorance wherever still available.

Rousseau was excellent on Sunday night, stacking five solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The sack was the talented edge rushers first full sack of the season and coincided with him playing a season-high 70 percent of the snaps. Hopefully, this is a sign of good things to come. Fire him up as a DL3 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Jaelan got his first sack of the season in Week 5, finishing the afternoon with three solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Phillips will look to keep the good times rolling in Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against a Los Angeles Chargers team missing both of their starting tackles. Start him with confidence for Week 6 despite the otherwise slow start.

Robinson notched his first sack of the season in Week 5, finishing the afternoon with two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. A'Shawn lost his DT eligibility on Yahoo for some reason, making him someone who should remain glued to benches despite his proven upside. Treat him as a DT2 option in DT leagues (on other providers), but those looking for DL (or DT on Yahoo) should look elsewhere.

Maliek impressed in Week 5, generating two solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. The defensive tackle is up to 3.5 sacks on the season, with all of them coming in two of his last three games. Collins has DT1 appeal for plus matchups and is a sneaky DL3 option for a plus Week 6 against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Make the add where needed.

Ossai is starting to heat up for the Bengals, most recently tallying one solo, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 61 percent of the snaps. Ossai has now recorded a sack in two of his last three games. The Bengals edge rusher has played over 60 percent of the snaps in four of his five contests, giving him a safe enough role to trust as a DL3/4 option where needed.

Eboigbe was excellent in Week 5, tallying three solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Eboigbe has recorded a sack in each of his last two games and saw his Week 4 effort get rewarded, as his snap share almost doubled from 36 percent to 71 percent in Week 5. He is an end in an odd front, so we should expect some peaks and valleys, but he is playing well enough to warrant attention, especially in deeper formats. Start him as a DL3/4 option for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins. Add Eboigbe where needed.

Wright was excellent in Week 5, tallying one solo, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Wright is starting to heat up, recording a sack in two of his last three. Wright played a season-high 51 percent of the snaps in Week 5, giving him deep league appeal as a bye week DL3/4. Start him where needed for a plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Sam Williams showed up in Week 5, racking up two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Williams played 46 percent of the snaps, marking the second week in a row that he's fallen under the 50 percent threshold. The first sack of his season is an encouraging sign, but amidst the falling snaps and strong play from other edge rotation members, Williams should remain benched for Week 6, despite a plus matchup against the Carolina Panthers. Look elsewhere for your Week 6 DL3.

SJD showed up in Week 5, tallying three solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Joseph-Day stays active in the solo department, so if he can start stringing some sacks together (this was his first of the season), he could become a DT1 option. For now, treat him as a DT2/DL4. Keep him benched unless that is what you are looking for.

Baun was excellent in Week 5, racking up seven solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Baun has been rolling to start the season, recording five or more solos in four of his five contests. Start him as a top-three option for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

Warner was excellent in Week 5, reeling off seven solos and five assists. Warner is the cream of the crop in IDP, stacking five or more solos in four straight games while adding value with peripheral contribution. Treat him as the LB1/IDP1 until further notice.

Brooks had a 'slow' night at the office on Sunday afternoon, racking up four solos, nine assists, and 0.5 sacks. Jordyn has recorded four or more solos in every game this season, including the scintillating 15 solos he tallied in Week 5. Start him as an LB1 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Wagner was excellent in Week 5, racking up eight solos and six assists. He has tallied five or more solos in three of his last four contests and four or more in four of five. Tap[ Wagner as an LB1 option for a plus matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Jack Campbell impressed in Week 5, tallying three solos, eight assists, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Cambpell has been rolling for the Lions and is an easy LB2 play for Sunday Night Football against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Robert Spillane was incredible in Week 5, tallying five solos, three assists, and one forced fumble. Spillane has started to heat up for New England, recording five or more solos in two of his last three games, and is beginning to look like the Spillane Patriots fans and IDP managers were expecting. Fire him up with confidence as a top-five option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Demario Davis continues to impress, most recently tallying seven solos, three assists, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Davis has seemingly found the fountain of youth as he has been in vintage form through the first five weeks of the season, recording five or more solos in four of five and cementing himself as an LB2 in or out of the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Okereke impressed in Week 5, racking up five solos and five assists. He has recorded four or more solos in four of his five contests, making him a solid LB2 option for Week 6 against the Philadelphia Eagles. Start him with confidence.

Zaire showed up in Week 5, racking up three solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Zaire has disappointed to start the season, recording three or fewer solos in four of his five contests. Treat him as an LB2 until he really gets it going, even with a splus matchup against the Arizona Cardinals on tap for Week 6.

Singleton showed up in Week 5, racking up four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Singleton has started to get it going after a slower IDP start to the season and has now put together three strong performances in a row. He has topped four solos just once all season, but has hit four or more in four of his five contests. Tap him as an LB2 option for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Jets.

Patrick Queen was excellent in Week 4, racking up eight solos, three assists, one sack, and three tackles for loss. Queen has been rolling to start the season and cemented himself as an LB2 option in the process. The Steelers linebacker had recorded five or more in three of his four contests and is an easy LB2 play for Week 6.

Quay Walker was excellent in Week 4, tallying six solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Quay has worked his way into the LB1 conversation on the strength of recording six or more solos in three of his four contests. Tap him as an LB1 option for a tasty Week 6 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Tremaine Edmunds was excellent in Week 4, tallying six solos and five assists. Tremaine has been on a heater to start the season, recording six solos in three straight contests. Tap Edmunds as an LB2 with LB1 upside for a plus Week 6 matchup against Washington.

Lavonte showed up in Week 5, tallying five solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. He has had a slow start to the season, but has been buoyed by two spike weeks. Lavonte has recorded five or more solos and a sack or pick in two of the last three, making him a safe LB2 option for what should be a fun Week 6 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Landman was excellent in Week 5, racking up eight solos, six assists, one tackle for loss, and three passes defended. Landman has had a strong start to his Rams tenure and has settled in as one of the better LB2 options. He has recorded four or more solos in three of his five contests and has contributed enough in the peripherals to keep him in the LB2 conversation. Tap him as an elite LB2 option for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against a banged-up Baltimore Ravens team.

Buchanan showed up in Week 5, tallying eight solos, seven assists, and one tackle for loss. Teddye has been starting over Trentom Simpson but saw an expanded role in Week 5, due to Roquan Smith being sidelined. This was easily his most impressive IDP putput of the season and marks his first game with more than four solos. Teddye is a strong LB3 play regardless of Roquan's Week 6 status. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Werner kept rolling in Week 5, tallying five solos and six assists. Werner has recorded five or more solos in four of his five contests, making him a borderline LB1 for the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Gray was at it again in Week 5, racking up six solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Gray is one of the hotter linebackers in fantasy right now and should be rostered in all competitive leagues while he is cooking. Gray has recorded five or more solos in three of four and has tallied 16 solos in his last two games. Tap Gray as a sneaky LB2 option for Week 6, thanks for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Payton Wilson was excellent in Week 4, racking up eight solos, five assists, and two tackles for loss. Wilson saw 87 percent of the snaps in Week 4, assuaging any concerns caused when the Steelers made Cole Holcomb the starter. Tap Wilson as an LB2 with LB1 upside, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Campbell impressed in Week 6, reeling off six solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Jihaad has quietly racked up five or more solos in three of his last four games, working his way into the bye week LB2 conversation in the process. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the New York Giants.

Knight was excellent in Week 5, reeling off four solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Demetrius has recorded four or more solos in three of his last five contests. Knight can be counted as an LB3 with LB2 appeal during the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Anzalone showed up in Week 5, racking up two solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and three passes defended. Anzalone has now recorded back-to-back spike weeks, but his floor still makes him someone to keep on benches where at all possible. Anzalone has recorded more than two solos just twice this season. Look elsewhere for your Week 6 LB3.

Shemar James turned heads in Week 5, stacking eight solos and seven assists. Shemar played 73 percent of the snaps and should continue to get a heavy snap count in Week 6. He is still more of a speculative add for those in shallower leagues, but those in 11 v 11 leagues or ocean-deep leagues should add Shemar immediately. Tap James as an LB3 option for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Dye impressed in Week 5, reeling off seven solos, four assists, and three tackles for loss. Dye is starting for the Chargers with Denzel Perryman sidelined and has finally flashed enough to warrant inclusion in the LB3 conversation. Dye has recorded more than three solos just once all season, making him an LB3 option for the bye weeks as long as Perryman remains sidelined. Add and start Dye where needed for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Rozeboom was excellent in Week 5, racking up five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Rozeboom has tallied five or more solos in three of five, but just one solo in the other two. Consider him a low-end LB2 due to the boom-or-bust nature of his production thus far. Treat him as such despite the plus Week 6 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Simpson showed up in Week 5, tallying four solos, six assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Trenton disappointed as a starter, leading to his demotion, but he got the start this past weekend with Roquan Smith sidelined. SImpson has ocean deep league appeal but should be benched in all 12-man leagues, even if Roquan misses another game. Look elsewhere for your Week 6 LB3.

Muasu was excellent in Week 5, tallying six solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Darius played a season high 46 percent of the snaps in Week 5, but has not been productive enough in his other contests to suggest for Week 6. Leave him on benches despite what projects to be a busy night against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Pratt got picked up quickly by the LB-needy Colts, but it may take him some time before he gets acclimated to the playbook and, as a result, receives significant enough snaps to trust in lineups. Take a wait-and-see approach for now and leave him on benches for Week 6.

Chubb stayed hot in Week 5, tallying one solo, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Chubb is up to four sacks on the season and has recorded at least one sack in four of his five contests. Fire him up as a strong DL2 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against a Los Angeles Chargers team missing both of their starting offensive tackles.

Herbig continued to impress in Week 4, tallying three solos, two assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Herbig has bullied his way into the DL2 conversation with plus matchups and will remain one until Alex Highsmith returns. Herbig has played well enough to be given an expanded role when Highsmith does return, but expectations should be tempered.

Minkah was excellent in Week 5, racking up six solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Fitzpatrick has tallied four or more solos in four of his five contests and has started to get it going in the peripherals. Continue to treat him as a DB1 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

DeShon Elliott was back in the lineup in Week 4 and responded with four solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, one interception, and two passes defended. Elliott is an easy DB3 play when healthy and has recorded four or more solos in both of his games played. He has some matchup-based DB2 upside, something he will have when the Steelers come off bye in Week 6 to face the Cleveland Browns.

Byard went off in Week 4, tallying five solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, two interceptions, and two passes defended. Byard has worked his way back into the DB1 mix on the strength of five solos in three of his four contests to go with three interceptions in four games. Treat him as just that for a plus Week 6 matchup against Washington.

Lake was excellent in Week 5, notching seven solos, four assists, and one pass defended. Quentin has tallied five solos in two straight and four or more in three of his five contests overall. He will be back in the DB1 mix for Week 6, thanks to a saliva-inducing matchup against the Cooper Rush led Baltimore Ravens. Start Lake with confidence everywhere.

Sigle shone on Thursday night, stacking seven solos, six assists, and one pass defended. Marques has tallied five or more solos in three of his five contests and in each of his last two. There is going to be some inconsistency, but Marques is an easy DB2 play for the bye weeks. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. Add Sigle wherever possible.

Xavier Watts was at it again in Week 4, notching two solos, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Watts has recorded six solos or a pick in every game so far and has been one of the catalysts for a Falcons defense that is turning some heads. Tap Watts as a borderline DB2 option as long as he stays hot.

Sainsristill was excellent in Week 5, racking up seven solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Sainristiill has recorded a pick in two straight games and has notched three or more solos in four straight. Tap him as a DB1/DB3 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Kerby Joseph showed up in Week 5, tallying three solos, one assist, one interception, and two passes defended. Joseph has failed to top three solos in any game this season, but has hauled in an interception in three of his five contests. Tap Kerby as a DB3 option where needed for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs on Sunday Night Football.

Sanker impressed in Week 5, reeling off six solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Sanker has tallied four or more solos in three of four games since being given an expanded role, and makes for a strong DB3 with DB2 upside. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Quan showed up in Week 5, tallying six solos, three assists, and one forced fumble. This was just the second time all season that Martin has recorded four or more solos, so only plug him into lineups if you're desperate. Keep him benched wherever possible despite the tasty matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Coby Bryant was excellent in Week 5, tallying seven solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. Bryant has been impressive thus far, recording six or more solos or a pick in four of his five contests. We would like to see more consistency in the solo department, but you can't argue with the fantasy production. Tap Bryant as a top-25 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Williams showed up in Week 4, racking up five solos and five assists. Williams is starting to show signs of the DB3 with DB2 upside we expected him to be, tallying four or more solos in two consecutive contests. Start him where needed for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Jaylen Watson showed up in Week 5, racking up four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Watson has been producing at a high level for fantasy managers, putting together three strong weeks in his five contests. Start Watson as a CB1/DB3 option where needed.

Eric Murray showed up in Week 5, tallying five solos, three assists, and one pass defended against the Kansas City Chiefs on Monday Night Football. Murray has had two strong weeks on the season, while being a non-factor in two others. Tap him as a bye week filler DB3/4 where needed for Week 6's matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Dadrion Taylor-Demerson impressed in Week 5, tallying four solos, one interception, and two passes defended on 64 percent of the snaps. DTD has four solos in three straight and has recorded a pick in two of them. DTD deserves some DB3 love as long as he is starting for the Cardinals. Start Dadrion where needed as a DB3 option for a tasty Week 6 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Ronnie Hickman was excellent in Week 5, racking up six solos and four assists. Hickman has produced at a DB1 level over the past two weeks and should be inserted into lineups while he is coolking. Start him where possible for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Kool-Aid went off in Week 5, tallying three solos, one assist, two interceptions, and three passes defended. McKinstry has put together three strong weeks in his five contests and makes for an intriguing CB1 option ahead of a Week 6 date with the New England Patriots. Tap him as a CB1/DB3/4 where needed.

Let's go deep. Juanyeh Thomas was excellent in Week 5, tallying five solos and five assists on 100 percent of the snaps. Thomas got the start for Malik Hooker (toe, now on IR) and should see a similar role for the next three games, minimum. Deep league managers should add Juanyeh wherever available. Start him as an easy DB3 option for Week 6, thanks to a plus matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Mekhi Blackmon showed up in Week 5, tallying four solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Blackmon has strung two spike weeks together and has registered four solos in four straight. Tap him as a CB1/DB3 option for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Marcus Jones was impressive in Week 5, racking up five solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and two passes defended. Jones has put together two excellent weeks in a row, but has been buoyed by a return TD and an interception. His strong play puts him in the mix for CB leagues, but those in DB leagues may want to look elsewhere for Week 6, despite the plus matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Tyrique Stevenson was excellent in Week 4, tallying four solos, two assists, one fumble recovery, one interception, and two passes defended. Tyrique has some DB3 appeal during the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 6 matchup against the Chicago Bears.
